(so the serializer acts like a translator.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Example idea:) Tj
T*
(SensorData object in Django -> JSON like:) Tj
T*
({) Tj
T*
(  "id": 1,) Tj
T*
(  "temperature": "24.50",) Tj
T*
(  "humidity": "52.00",) Tj
T*
(  "created_at": "2026-03-23T10:30:00Z") Tj
T*
(}) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(views.py) Tj
T*
(Your home view returns a simple JSON message for the root URL.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Your SensorDataViewSet uses DRF ModelViewSet.) Tj
T*
(That is a ready-made class that automatically gives common API actions like:) Tj
T*
(- list all sensor readings) Tj
T*
(- get one reading) Tj
T*
(- create a reading) Tj
T*
(- update a reading) Tj
T*
(- delete a reading) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(In your code:) Tj
T*
(- queryset = SensorData.objects.all\(\) means it reads all SensorData rows.) Tj
T*
(- serializer_class = SensorDataSerializer means it converts those rows using the) Tj
T*
(  serializer.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(urls.py) Tj
T*
(At the app level, you use DefaultRouter.) Tj
T*
(That router automatically creates routes for the viewset.) Tj
T*
(Registering "sensor-data" creates routes such as:) Tj
T*
(- /sensor-data/) Tj
T*
(- /sensor-data/1/) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(At the project level, you include monitoring.urls under /api/.) Tj
T*
(That means the final endpoint becomes:) Tj
T*
(- /api/sensor-data/) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(So routing works like this:) Tj
T*
(project urls.py -> /api/ -> monitoring.urls -> router -> SensorDataViewSet) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(3. Data Flow from Database to Frontend) Tj
T*
(The backend flow is:) Tj
T*
(1. A reading exists in the database.) Tj
T*
(2. Django loads it through the SensorData model.) Tj
T*
(3. SensorDataViewSet gets the queryset.) Tj
T*
(4. SensorDataSerializer turns it into JSON.) Tj
T*
(5. Django REST Framework sends it as an HTTP response.) Tj
T*
(6. React fetches that response.) Tj
ET
endstream
